author: Tara Reynolds
text:
The only problem is…

I can’t seem to find the trail. 
I can no longer see my camp sight. 
I had no fire burning to search for the light, smoke or smell of smoke because of the wind. 
I had absolutely NO sense of direction. 

I was panicked. 
I was lost… ::::TBC::::

author: Tara Reynolds
Tara Reynolds
text:
I desperately try and remember if I walked to that spot and put the tent up facing the direction I came from. 

That seems reasonable.  
Another light crack of thunder and I take off in that direction. 

The sky is getting darker by the minute. The wind is so strong. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
All around me looked the same. 

Just woods. 
There was nothing that stood out to me. Nothing to give me a clue as to what direction I needed to go in to get back on the trail. 

I feel another drop of rain as I look back at my tent. The direction it was facing. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
The weight off all that would just bog me down. 

I grabbed what I absolutely needed and took off. 

About 300 feet away from my camp sight, I spin on my heel to take in my surroundings. 
I feel the first rain drop hit my nose. 

Was I going the right way? >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
I better do it now. 

I started to gather up all the camping supplies when I hear a crack of thunder. 

Fuck it …
That was my response. 
I was rich as fuck. I could buy more camping shit if I ever decide to try this again. 
Besides … I needed to get my ass out of here. >

author: Tara Reynolds
Tara Reynolds
text:
Should have been my top priority. 

If I said I wasn’t a bit uneasy… I’d be lying. 
I was getting scared. 

I had no idea if the stakes I drove would securely hold my tent to the ground. 
I had no clue if this tent leaked…was it even waterproof?  >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
Seems pretty logical, right? 

Except for the fact..that logic was foreign to me. 
I was more focused on comfort…food…Important things like that. 

Although…at this moment, as I watch the storm clouds roll in and I can feel the wind pick up drastically…checking the weather >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
[Camping 101 …

Always check the weather forecast before you set up camp.

author: Tara Reynolds
Tara Reynolds
text:
I find a place to rest for a little while and drink some water before I begin finding a place off the trail to set up camp. 
I look around the area and laugh a little at myself. I can’t believe I’m actually doing this… That I’m out here, in the woods alone. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text: I had no way of knowing, because I was tech-less…but I had probably hiked through the woods about 2 miles…although it felt like 6 with this backpack full of all my supplies and a small tent strapped to it. >

author: Tara Reynolds
Tara Reynolds
text:
I wanted no distractions at all. 
So I turned my phone off and locked it inside my vehicle.

I take in a deep breath and begin this adventure on the trail in front of me.  > https://t.co/lO6ho5hsPe

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
Another reason to be thankful no one else was around to see my clumsiness…Then I have to catch my breath for a few minutes before I can set off on my long hike. 
I instinctively take out my phone to look at the time.  I realize at that moment that I didn’t need my phone. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
The whole point of doing this was to be completely isolated from people, media, electronics etc…
But especially people. 

After driving around longer than I wanted to …I finally decide on a place and hope it’s fairly vacant. 

I only struggle for 20 minutes with my backpack…>

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
I am leaving my door (The follow button) WIDE open.
I will welcome anyone back into my life that wishes to be there. 

I’m extending a large olive branch. 

Whether anyone takes it or not is up to you.  
But I, for one,  am setting myself free.  ❤️❤️ >

author: Tara Reynolds
text: Today I am letting it all go.  I am forgiving myself for hurting others and forgiving those who have hurt me.  For me, the slate is wiped clean. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
And we ALL need to learn (again) that this place is just Role Play and  drop the needless hate for others. 

“Holding a grudge doesn’t make you strong; it makes you bitter. Forgiving doesn’t make you weak; it sets you free.” >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
Not one person here is perfect. No one is as pure and innocent as we try to portray.  
We have ALL been the villain in someone else’s story and we have ALL been victims in our own. 
People change.  People learn and people grow up. 
We all evolve.  >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
We are all hypocrites. We are all human. This world is full of double standards and we have all made poor decisions and choices.  
We have all been caught up in the moment or situation.  Did and said things we later regretted. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
We spend more time gossiping and spreading ruthless rumors than we do on actual writing. 
In reality, we hate X for doing something unforgettable to us that we have done to others in the past in one way or another. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
We’ve held grudges, jealousy and hate for so long that most of us don’t even remember why they formed in the first place. 
All we know is that we’re supposed to hate X and so should all our friends. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
Because of all factors … hate, jealousy and resentment formed. Manipulation, inaccurate gossip and assumptions were made and so were “enemies.”
We developed grudges. We “warned” fellow RPs of others and thought of alters…”hidden alters” as the work of the devil.>

author: Tara Reynolds
text: Character break ups became more like an ugly RL divorce and if your partner moved on, the new mate was a home wrecking, evil, asshole that should be tarred and feathered for the rest of their RP days. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text: The “in character” banter came to a screeching stop because we could no longer differentiate between real life and the role play life of a character.  It all blurred. It was taken out of context.  It was taken personal.  >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
Fast forward about 5-6 years. 
Somewhere along the way shit got personal. Real life became blurred into role play and hate, along with “love” and possessiveness developed for the writer instead of the character…. I personally blame the app Kik.  Always have.  [Shrugs] >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:
[Deep inhale] …Once upon a time in a galaxy far far away…I stumbled upon a strange yet intriguing world on the other side of Twitter called Role Play…
It was character driven. It was fun. It was an escape and it wasn’t taken personal.  It was just Role Play. >

author: Tara Reynolds
text:

This might be a long one. 
(That’s what she said) 

I’m not really sure how to start, 
so bare with me. 
Hopefully I’ll have some valid points and inspiring words mixed in the intermittent rambling. >
